{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614702"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16373"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16373"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9064"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74748"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9064"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60234"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"10335"},{"type":"tags","id":"10336"},{"type":"tags","id":"10350"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21549"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21551"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74748"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is studying the anatomical organisation of the brainstem. The brainstem can be divided into three longitudinal subdivisions from ventral to dorsal: the basis, tegmentum, and tectum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most consistently found in the basis of the brainstem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cranial nerve nuclei","Corticospinal tract","Medial longitudinal fasciculus","Reticular formation","Lemnisci"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe brainstem can be divided into three longitudinal divisions from ventral to dorsal: basis (ventral), tegmentum (middle), and tectum (dorsal). Each division contains specific structures and pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorticospinal tract\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the basis (ventral portion) of the brainstem, specifically in the pyramids of the medulla and the ventral pons. The basis primarily contains descending motor pathways including the corticospinal tract and corticopontine fibres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecranial nerve nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E are located in the tegmentum (middle portion) of the brainstem, not the basis. These nuclei are arranged in functional columns and are essential for various sensory and motor functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial longitudinal fasciculus\u003C/strong\u003E is found in the tegmentum, where it coordinates eye movements and maintains balance through connections with vestibular and oculomotor nuclei.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ereticular formation\u003C/strong\u003E is a complex network of nuclei and fibres located primarily in the tegmentum, involved in arousal, sleep, and various autonomic functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elemnisci\u003C/strong\u003E are ascending sensory pathways located in the tegmentum, carrying information about touch, proprioception, and pain to higher centres.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The brainstem has three longitudinal divisions: basis (ventral), tegmentum (middle), and tectum (dorsal)","The basis contains descending motor pathways including the corticospinal tract and corticopontine fibres","The tegmentum contains ascending sensory pathways, cranial nerve nuclei, and the reticular formation"],"references":["Natali AL, Reddy V, Bordoni B. Neuroanatomy, Corticospinal Cord Tract. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30571044.","Perez MA, Cohen LG. The corticospinal system and transcranial magnetic stimulation in stroke. Top Stroke Rehabil. 2009 Jul-Aug;16(4):254-69. doi: 10.1310/tsr1604-254. PMID: 19740731; PMCID: PMC4886556.Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60234"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16373"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60234"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T20:54:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T21:48:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9064"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74748"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoj